725931f-c.title: Queens: 160th Street - Archer Avenue
725931f-c.text:
160th Street, north from Archer Avenue, near the Long Island
Railroad tracks. On the left is the John Everett house, three
stories high. It was also known as the Continental Hall where
the Jamaica Odd Fellows used to meet.
View 2 shows the east side of the street. the house with the
peak-roof having been owned by H.C..Ham in 1873.On the left, the
peak-roof house with the stores )uilt in front of it, was owned
by Ben Everett, and by J. B. Remsen in 1873.
View 3 shows the H. C. Ham house, at the N. E. corner of Archer
Avenue, after half the building has been cut away when Archer Avenue
(right) was cut through. It is now being used as a store for new
and second hand building waterials. To the left of the drive-in
is the Ben Everett house. 160th Street was formely Washington
Street.
Views 1, : Eugene L Arwbruster Collection  1924

725932f-a.title: Queens: 160th Street - Archer Avenue
725932f-a.text:
160th Street, adjoining the N.E. corner of Archer Avenue,
showing two very old homes with built-in store fronts, across
which is seen the National Title Guarahtee Trust Company Building
on Jamaica Avenue. In 1891 the owner of the first house was
S. Edwards and in 1873 I.B. Remsen. It was also known as the
Ben Everett house. See also other views.
P. L. Sperr  March 30, 1932
